To find where the graph intersects the $y$-axis, we substitute $x = 0$ into the function.

$$
\begin{aligned} 
f(0) &= \frac{3(0) + 6}{0 - 4} \\ 
f(0) &= \frac{6}{-4} \\ 
f(0) &= -\frac{3}{2} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, the $y$-intercept is at $\left(0, -\frac{3}{2}\right)$.

The question asks for the form $f(x)=\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}$. To achieve this, we combine the terms into a single rational fraction by finding a common denominator.

The common denominator is $x-1$. We multiply the constant $6$ by $\frac{x-1}{x-1}$:

$$
\begin{aligned} 
f(x) &= 6\left(\frac{x-1}{x-1}\right) + \frac{2}{x-1} \\ 
&= \frac{6(x-1) + 2}{x-1} \\ 
&= \frac{6x - 6 + 2}{x-1} \\ 
&= \frac{6x - 4}{x-1} 
\end{aligned}
$$
